    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the confusion. The interest on a student loan is typically calculated using the following formula:\n\nInterest for the month = (Remaining Principal Balance) x (Monthly Interest Rate)\n\nThe Monthly Interest Rate is determined by dividing the Annual Percentage Rate (APR) of the loan by 12 (the number of months in a year). So, if you have a student loan with an APR of 5%, the monthly interest rate would be 5% / 12, which equals approximately 0.4167%.\n\nEach month, the interest is calculated based on the remaining principal balance, and that interest amount is added to the loan balance. The rest of your payment goes towards reducing the principal. This is why it might feel like the principal isn't going down as fast as you'd expect, especially when you're making full payments. The interest is calculated on the remaining balance, so as the principal decreases, so does the interest amount, but it can take some time to see a significant reduction in the principal balance.",
